    summary: '1929年纽约股市崩盘引爆的全球性经济危机，导致大规模失业与贫困，深刻改变了各国经济政策，间接催生了二战。',
    summaryEn: 'The 1929 Wall Street Crash triggered a global economic crisis of mass unemployment and poverty, fundamentally transforming economic policy worldwide and indirectly contributing to World War II.',
    description: '1929年10月29日（"黑色星期二"），纽约证券交易所股价暴跌，宣告了持续整个1930年代的大萧条的开始。危机迅速波及全球：美国失业率从1929年的3%飙升至1933年的25%，工业生产下降近50%；德国失业人口超过600万；全球贸易额萎缩60%以上；数千家银行倒闭，储户一生的积蓄化为乌有。这场危机催生了两种截然不同的经济政策：美国罗斯福的"新政"（政府干预、社会保障、公共工程）和德国的纳粹军事凯恩斯主义（重整军备、高速公路建设）。1930年代的全球大萧条是民主制度面临的最严峻考验之一：它摧毁了德国魏玛共和国，滋养了纳粹主义和日本军国主义的崛起，成为二战最重要的经济根源之一。',
    descriptionEn: 'On October 29, 1929 ("Black Tuesday"), stock prices on the New York Stock Exchange collapsed, inaugurating the Great Depression that lasted through the 1930s. The crisis rapidly went global: US unemployment surged from 3% in 1929 to 25% in 1933, industrial production fell nearly 50%; over six million Germans were jobless; global trade contracted more than 60%; thousands of banks failed, wiping out depositors\' life savings. The crisis spawned two starkly different policy responses: Roosevelt\'s New Deal in America (government intervention, social security, public works) and Nazi military Keynesianism in Germany (rearmament, autobahn construction). The Great Depression was one of the severest tests democracy ever faced: it destroyed Germany\'s Weimar Republic, nourished the rise of Nazism and Japanese militarism, and ranks as one of the most important economic causes of World War II.',
