    summary: '人类历史上最接近核战争的13天危机，美苏在古巴部署苏联核导弹的对峙中以赫鲁晓夫撤出导弹、肯尼迪承诺不入侵古巴告终。',
    summaryEn: 'The thirteen-day crisis that brought humanity closer to nuclear war than ever before, resolved when Khrushchev withdrew Soviet missiles from Cuba in exchange for Kennedy\'s pledge not to invade Cuba.',
    description: '1962年10月16日至28日的古巴导弹危机是冷战中最危险的对抗。10月14日，美国U-2侦察机发现苏联正在古巴秘密部署中程弹道核导弹，射程可覆盖美国东部大部分地区。肯尼迪总统在经过了激烈的内部辩论（军方主张空袭或入侵）后，于10月22日发表电视讲话向全国公布局势，宣布对古巴实施海军"隔离"（温和说法，实为封锁）。世界屏息而待。10月27日（"黑色星期六"），一架美国U-2侦察机在古巴上空被击落，另一架在苏联领空迷航，美苏海军在封锁线对峙，世界距核战争仅一步之遥。10月28日，赫鲁晓夫宣布撤出导弹，作为交换，美国秘密承诺从土耳其撤出已过时的木星导弹并公开承诺不入侵古巴。危机后，美苏建立了"热线"并开始了战略武器控制谈判。',
    descriptionEn: 'The Cuban Missile Crisis (October 16-28, 1962) was the Cold War\'s most dangerous confrontation. On October 14, US U-2 spy planes discovered Soviet medium-range ballistic nuclear missiles being secretly deployed in Cuba, capable of striking most of the eastern United States. After intense internal debate (the military advocated airstrikes or invasion), President Kennedy addressed the nation on October 22, announcing a naval "quarantine" (the diplomatic term for a blockade) of Cuba. The world held its breath. On October 27 ("Black Saturday"), a US U-2 was shot down over Cuba, another strayed into Soviet airspace, and US and Soviet naval forces faced off at the quarantine line—humanity stood one step from nuclear war. On October 28, Khrushchev announced the missile withdrawal; in return, the US secretly agreed to withdraw its obsolete Jupiter missiles from Turkey and publicly pledged not to invade Cuba. The crisis led to the establishment of a direct Moscow-Washington "hotline" and the beginning of strategic arms control negotiations.',
